WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.184 --> 00:00:10.100
SPEAKER: His New York
Times best-selling book,

00:00:10.100 --> 00:00:10.970
"Work Rules--

00:00:10.970 --> 00:00:13.490
Insights from Inside
Google to Transform

00:00:13.490 --> 00:00:17.900
How You Live and Lead," has
been published in 24 languages

00:00:17.900 --> 00:00:20.780
and garnered numerous
book of the year honors.

00:00:20.780 --> 00:00:24.470
From 2006 to 2016, Laszlo
was senior vice president

00:00:24.470 --> 00:00:27.290
of People Operations and a
member of Google's management

00:00:27.290 --> 00:00:32.390
team, growing the company
from 6,000 to 72,000 employees

00:00:32.390 --> 00:00:35.390
and ensuring the firm's culture
remained innovative and robust

00:00:35.390 --> 00:00:36.560
throughout.

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:39.650
During his tenure, Google
was recognized over 150 times

00:00:39.650 --> 00:00:41.622
as an exceptional
employer, including

00:00:41.622 --> 00:00:43.580
being named the number
one best company to work

00:00:43.580 --> 00:00:45.920
for in the United
States seven times

00:00:45.920 --> 00:00:49.630
and every year since 2012,
which was when I joined, so just

00:00:49.630 --> 00:00:51.050
hold onto that one.

00:00:51.050 --> 00:00:53.340
It must have something
to do with this.

00:00:53.340 --> 00:00:56.540
Laszlo is credited with creating
the field of people analytics,

00:00:56.540 --> 00:00:58.970
the application of
academic quality rigor

00:00:58.970 --> 00:01:01.910
and Google paced innovation
to people management.

00:01:01.910 --> 00:01:05.450
He also led development of
the Google Cloud Jobs API

00:01:05.450 --> 00:01:07.779
and what is now known
as Google for Jobs

00:01:07.779 --> 00:01:09.320
with the goal of
solving unemployment

00:01:09.320 --> 00:01:11.960
by better matching people and
jobs through applied machine

00:01:11.960 --> 00:01:14.060
learning and people analytics.

00:01:14.060 --> 00:01:17.381
He joined Google from the
General Electric company

00:01:17.381 --> 00:01:19.130
and beforehand was a
management consultant

00:01:19.130 --> 00:01:20.555
at McKinsey and
Company, probably

00:01:20.555 --> 00:01:22.340
a better management
consultant than what

00:01:22.340 --> 00:01:23.900
you heard from me earlier.

00:01:23.900 --> 00:01:26.810
He has served on the boards
of Pomona College, Evolve,

00:01:26.810 --> 00:01:27.722
and whoops--

00:01:27.722 --> 00:01:29.180
I'm going to
mispronounce this one.

00:01:29.180 --> 00:01:30.980
I'm just going to
scoot right by it--

00:01:30.980 --> 00:01:34.130
another one.

00:01:34.130 --> 00:01:36.950
In 2010, he was named
human resources executive

00:01:36.950 --> 00:01:42.480
of the year, and in 2015, the
HR professional of the decade.

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:45.650
He briefly was ranked number one
in the world in the video game

00:01:45.650 --> 00:01:46.490
"Assassin's Creed."

00:01:49.226 --> 00:01:50.600
Laszlo earned a
bachelor's degree

00:01:50.600 --> 00:01:52.670
in international relations
from Pomona College,

00:01:52.670 --> 00:01:55.155
graduating in three years,
and an MBA from the Yale

00:01:55.155 --> 00:01:56.030
School of Management.

00:01:56.030 --> 00:01:57.640
Please join me in
welcoming Laszlo.

00:01:57.640 --> 00:01:59.614
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:59.614 --> 00:02:00.780
LASZLO BOCK: That was great.

00:02:00.780 --> 00:02:02.480
I wish my mom could
have heard all that.

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:03.725
That was terrific.

00:02:03.725 --> 00:02:04.600
How's everyone doing?

00:02:04.600 --> 00:02:05.520
AUDIENCE: Great.

00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:08.330
LASZLO BOCK: OK, nothing
standing between lunch and you,

00:02:08.330 --> 00:02:09.979
except me.

00:02:09.979 --> 00:02:12.710
So I just have like
200 or 300 slides

00:02:12.710 --> 00:02:14.990
I want to walk you through.

00:02:14.990 --> 00:02:17.560
It is-- I was going to
say it's great to be here.

00:02:17.560 --> 00:02:20.360
It's super weird, actually,
to be back at Google.

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:22.670
I left at the end of the
year, and I don't even

00:02:22.670 --> 00:02:24.660
think they had this
building at the time.

00:02:24.660 --> 00:02:25.610
So it's kind of--

00:02:25.610 --> 00:02:28.340
I just got to get
that off my chest.

00:02:28.340 --> 00:02:30.660
It's also great to be here.

00:02:30.660 --> 00:02:34.010
It's actually a real
privilege, because there's

00:02:34.010 --> 00:02:36.290
a long history of
teaching and caring

00:02:36.290 --> 00:02:39.420
about education in my
family and in my own life.

00:02:39.420 --> 00:02:42.410
And so more than anything else,
I want to thank all of you

00:02:42.410 --> 00:02:45.109
for the work you do
every single day,

00:02:45.109 --> 00:02:47.400
for all these kids, who are
the future of this country.

00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:48.590
And I'm sure you've heard
this again and again

00:02:48.590 --> 00:02:50.990
and again, but it's
the most important job

00:02:50.990 --> 00:02:53.450
there is on this planet.

00:02:53.450 --> 00:02:55.640
My mother was a teacher.

00:02:55.640 --> 00:02:58.490
I was born in Romania, and
she was an English teacher.

00:02:58.490 --> 00:03:00.709
And we defected.

00:03:00.709 --> 00:03:01.250
We snuck out.

00:03:01.250 --> 00:03:02.910
We stayed in a refugee
camp in Austria.

00:03:02.910 --> 00:03:05.450
We came to the United
States in 1974,

00:03:05.450 --> 00:03:08.990
and my mother and her side
of the family are Jewish,

00:03:08.990 --> 00:03:11.770
and what she always--
and so, you know,

00:03:11.770 --> 00:03:16.160
if you're from Europe, and you
know, my mom was born in 1945,

00:03:16.160 --> 00:03:18.930
she had lost chunks of her
family in the Holocaust.

00:03:18.930 --> 00:03:20.750
They were murdered
in the Holocaust.

00:03:20.750 --> 00:03:23.600
And my mom always raised
me with the phrase,

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:26.400
they can never take
away your education.

00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:30.050
That's one thing they, whoever
they are, can never take away.

00:03:30.050 --> 00:03:32.630
So what you're doing is
the most important thing

00:03:32.630 --> 00:03:34.244
there is out there.

00:03:34.244 --> 00:03:36.660
I dabbled a little in education
when I was in high school.

00:03:36.660 --> 00:03:38.240
I worked as a summer
school teacher

00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:41.030
for three years teaching
a debate program

00:03:41.030 --> 00:03:45.830
in a forensic debate thing
the school had set up.

00:03:45.830 --> 00:03:48.080
I spent a summer teaching
in Japan, teaching English,

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:48.871
like everyone does.

00:03:48.871 --> 00:03:50.499
I did a bunch of tutoring.

00:03:50.499 --> 00:03:52.040
It still sounds
weird, but I remember

00:03:52.040 --> 00:03:55.582
there was one guy I
tutored, and my gift to him

00:03:55.582 --> 00:03:58.040
at the end of the tutoring was
a copy of "The Autobiography

00:03:58.040 --> 00:04:00.770
of Malcolm X," which,
coming from me,

00:04:00.770 --> 00:04:04.340
was probably a pretty
weird thing for him.

00:04:04.340 --> 00:04:06.011
But he, years later,
followed up with me

00:04:06.011 --> 00:04:07.010
and thanked me for that.

00:04:07.010 --> 00:04:09.560
And the impact you
have, as you know,

00:04:09.560 --> 00:04:11.930
you don't feel in that
year all the time.

00:04:11.930 --> 00:04:14.540
You feel it five years later,
10 years later, 15 years later,

00:04:14.540 --> 00:04:16.623
if you're lucky enough to
have students come back.

00:04:16.623 --> 00:04:18.380
So I'm incredibly
grateful for the work

00:04:18.380 --> 00:04:20.390
you do, and it is
a sincere honor

00:04:20.390 --> 00:04:22.580
to be here and be
talking to you.

00:04:22.580 --> 00:04:25.580
So I hope you find it helpful.

00:04:25.580 --> 00:04:28.760
I was-- I did leave
Google fairly recently.

00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:32.190
And this was my mission
when I was at Google.

00:04:32.190 --> 00:04:35.490
So I led People Operations,
and this was it.

00:04:35.490 --> 00:04:37.860
And the way we came
up with this mission--

00:04:37.860 --> 00:04:41.280
find people, grow
them, keep them--

00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:43.080
we had our first
global get-together

00:04:43.080 --> 00:04:45.450
for the People Operations team.

00:04:45.450 --> 00:04:47.980
And literally, 30
minutes before it,

00:04:47.980 --> 00:04:50.670
we had no idea what our unifying
mission was going to be.

00:04:50.670 --> 00:04:53.220
This amazing woman
named Judy Gilbert said,

00:04:53.220 --> 00:04:54.930
isn't it just
these three things?

00:04:54.930 --> 00:04:57.750
And so the unifying spirit
behind everything we did

00:04:57.750 --> 00:05:01.277
was find exceptional people,
grow them as fast and as much

00:05:01.277 --> 00:05:03.360
as you can, give them the
tools, the capabilities,

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:05.609
the experiences to get better,
and then keep them here

00:05:05.609 --> 00:05:07.780
as long as possible.

00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:08.839
I recently left.

00:05:08.839 --> 00:05:10.380
I left Google at
the end of last year

00:05:10.380 --> 00:05:13.530
and a few months ago, started
a company called Humu--

00:05:13.530 --> 00:05:15.510
not an education
company, unfortunately.

00:05:15.510 --> 00:05:17.010
And we're actually
still in stealth,

00:05:17.010 --> 00:05:18.450
so I can't say
too much about it.

00:05:18.450 --> 00:05:20.715
But the underlying
idea is how to make

00:05:20.715 --> 00:05:22.590
work better and the
experience of work better

00:05:22.590 --> 00:05:24.660
for everyone in
every environment.

00:05:24.660 --> 00:05:27.240
And eventually, there may be
some education applications

00:05:27.240 --> 00:05:30.350
for students, but
I guess the stakes

00:05:30.350 --> 00:05:33.100
are a lot lower when dealing
with grownups than with kids.

00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:35.100
And so we start with
grownups, and then maybe we

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:36.500
eventually work our way to kids.

00:05:36.500 --> 00:05:38.530
But if you want
to learn more, you

00:05:38.530 --> 00:05:41.840
can sign up to
learn at humu.com.

00:05:41.840 --> 00:05:45.140
What I really want to
talk about is an epiphany

00:05:45.140 --> 00:05:48.110
I had when I was
at Google, which

00:05:48.110 --> 00:05:50.750
is we spend more
time working than we

00:05:50.750 --> 00:05:53.660
do anything else in our lives.

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:56.060
And it's a little
crazy, because think

00:05:56.060 --> 00:05:58.100
back to when you're, like,
in junior high school

00:05:58.100 --> 00:05:59.154
or high school.

00:05:59.154 --> 00:06:01.070
You're first starting
to discover that there's

00:06:01.070 --> 00:06:03.528
other people in your life you
might want to be romantically

00:06:03.528 --> 00:06:05.660
involved with, and you
start caring about stories

00:06:05.660 --> 00:06:08.243
like "Romeo and Juliet," and you
start thinking, somewhere out

00:06:08.243 --> 00:06:10.220
there, there is someone for me.

00:06:10.220 --> 00:06:12.320
And I'm going to find
that perfect person,

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:14.750
and I'm going to dedicate
my life to that person.

00:06:14.750 --> 00:06:16.860
I'm going to be
fulfilled and happy.

00:06:16.860 --> 00:06:22.670
And then you grow up, and
you find the person, usually.

00:06:22.670 --> 00:06:28.070
And you never get to see them,
because you spend all your time

00:06:28.070 --> 00:06:32.782
with all these bozos you got to
work with day in and day out.

00:06:32.782 --> 00:06:34.490
And there's a member
of our team at Humu,

00:06:34.490 --> 00:06:36.530
who, among other things,
she was a fourth grade

00:06:36.530 --> 00:06:39.290
teacher for a few years
at a local charter school.

00:06:39.290 --> 00:06:41.060
And she said, yeah,
this is a good chart,

00:06:41.060 --> 00:06:43.143
but what you should tell
the teachers is it really

00:06:43.143 --> 00:06:45.860
should just be work and sleep.

00:06:45.860 --> 00:06:48.530
Teachers don't get
the other stuff.

00:06:48.530 --> 00:06:51.260
But it seemed wrong to me
that for too many people,

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:52.580
it's a bad experience.

00:06:52.580 --> 00:06:53.995
Work is a means to an end.

00:06:53.995 --> 00:06:56.120
Amy Wrzesniewski is a
professor at Yale University,

00:06:56.120 --> 00:07:00.050
did a study that found in every
profession, about 30% of people

00:07:00.050 --> 00:07:00.890
find meaning in it.

00:07:00.890 --> 00:07:03.356
The other 2/3, not so much.

00:07:03.356 --> 00:07:04.730
And even in
professions you would

00:07:04.730 --> 00:07:07.550
expect everybody's fired up
about the meaning, right?

00:07:07.550 --> 00:07:09.974
Like nursing, like medicine.

00:07:09.974 --> 00:07:10.640
Like, it's fine.

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:11.600
I understand lawyers.

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:13.230
2/3 of them don't care.

00:07:13.230 --> 00:07:18.890
But for teachers, for people
in ministry, only about 1/3

00:07:18.890 --> 00:07:22.250
of them, because it's hard to
sustain that your whole career.

00:07:22.250 --> 00:07:23.000
You have bad days.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:23.874
You have bad moments.

00:07:23.874 --> 00:07:28.920
It just becomes a job after
the first 15 or 20 or 25 years.

00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:32.890
And so what we tried to figure
out while I was at Google was,

00:07:32.890 --> 00:07:34.140
how do you solve this problem?

00:07:34.140 --> 00:07:35.550
How do you make it better?

00:07:35.550 --> 00:07:38.030
And so they were kind
enough to let me write

00:07:38.030 --> 00:07:40.850
a book called "Work Rules."

00:07:40.850 --> 00:07:43.760
And the idea here was
to find some science

00:07:43.760 --> 00:07:45.800
and some information
about Google's experience,

00:07:45.800 --> 00:07:47.240
but more importantly, about
the rest of the world,

00:07:47.240 --> 00:07:48.560
about what works to
make work better.

00:07:48.560 --> 00:07:50.060
So there's a bunch
of stuff in here.

00:07:50.060 --> 00:07:52.370
The only reason I'm
mentioning it is all the money

00:07:52.370 --> 00:07:53.299
goes to charity.

00:07:53.299 --> 00:07:55.340
Actually, the publisher
keeps whatever they want,

00:07:55.340 --> 00:07:57.110
but I have donated
and will continue

00:07:57.110 --> 00:08:00.770
to donate all my money to
charities related to refugees

00:08:00.770 --> 00:08:04.012
and immigration issues,
to educational access,

00:08:04.012 --> 00:08:06.470
so giving kids who otherwise
won't have access to education

00:08:06.470 --> 00:08:07.970
or better educational
opportunities,

00:08:07.970 --> 00:08:09.660
and to veterans' charities, so.

00:08:09.660 --> 00:08:13.340
[APPLAUSE]

00:08:14.730 --> 00:08:17.081
It really like-- because
there's a good chunk

00:08:17.081 --> 00:08:19.580
of this which is Google stuff,
which isn't my story to tell.

00:08:19.580 --> 00:08:23.790
And it felt like it's not
mine to profit from either.

00:08:23.790 --> 00:08:26.450
So this is some of the
stuff that's in there.

00:08:26.450 --> 00:08:28.370
There's more in the book.

00:08:28.370 --> 00:08:31.160
I'm going to touch on
a few of these rules

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:34.690
that I think are particularly
apropos to teaching

00:08:34.690 --> 00:08:37.169
and the profession of not
just being in the classroom,

00:08:37.169 --> 00:08:40.250
but administering and running
educational institutions.

00:08:40.250 --> 00:08:41.640
And then we'll
have Q and A time,

00:08:41.640 --> 00:08:45.260
and I'm totally happy to
debate and discuss and learn,

00:08:45.260 --> 00:08:47.630
if I'm completely
wrong on this stuff,

00:08:47.630 --> 00:08:51.290
because I imagine I'm
probably 50% to 100% wrong

00:08:51.290 --> 00:08:52.550
on the education piece.

00:08:52.550 --> 00:08:56.374
So I look forward to that
part of the discussion.

00:08:56.374 --> 00:08:58.540
But whenever I talk about
stuff, and whenever people

00:08:58.540 --> 00:08:59.727
come to Google--

00:08:59.727 --> 00:09:01.060
you guys have seen the beanbags.

00:09:01.060 --> 00:09:02.080
You've seen the lava lamps.

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:04.330
You've seen, like, you know,
like clearly this company

00:09:04.330 --> 00:09:08.150
spends money on people.

00:09:08.150 --> 00:09:10.540
And I was once giving
a talk in Chicago

00:09:10.540 --> 00:09:13.630
to a group of heads of HR, and
somebody said, well, at Google,

00:09:13.630 --> 00:09:14.422
you can do this.

00:09:14.422 --> 00:09:15.880
You got all the
money in the world.

00:09:15.880 --> 00:09:17.380
You got 30% profit margins.

00:09:17.380 --> 00:09:18.130
You're everywhere.

00:09:18.130 --> 00:09:21.010
You got-- of course, you can do
all these things to make work

00:09:21.010 --> 00:09:22.840
better for your employees.

00:09:22.840 --> 00:09:25.870
I'm an insurance company
on a state pension fund.

00:09:25.870 --> 00:09:26.560
I can't do this.

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:30.125
And before I could respond,
somebody stood up in the room

00:09:30.125 --> 00:09:31.500
and raised his
hand, and he said,

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:34.120
well, actually, basically,
what they're talking about

00:09:34.120 --> 00:09:35.980
is giving people freedom.

00:09:35.980 --> 00:09:40.170
And freedom is free.

00:09:40.170 --> 00:09:42.630
Giving people in your
workforce more freedom

00:09:42.630 --> 00:09:44.880
doesn't cost you
anything, except giving up

00:09:44.880 --> 00:09:47.420
a little bit of control and
allowing them to do things.

00:09:47.420 --> 00:09:49.170
And then in the course
of writing the book

00:09:49.170 --> 00:09:51.122
and being at Google in
sessions like these,

00:09:51.122 --> 00:09:53.580
there's all these companies
from very different industries,

00:09:53.580 --> 00:09:56.160
very different businesses,
very different economics,

00:09:56.160 --> 00:10:01.110
who look very different from
Google but feel very similar.

00:10:01.110 --> 00:10:04.070
So my favorite example is
a company called Wegmans.

00:10:04.070 --> 00:10:05.730
Is anyone here
from the Northeast?

00:10:05.730 --> 00:10:06.990
Any Wegmans fans?

00:10:06.990 --> 00:10:08.156
AUDIENCE: I just went there.

00:10:08.156 --> 00:10:09.100
It was awesome.

00:10:09.100 --> 00:10:10.766
LASZLO BOCK: He said
he just went there.

00:10:10.766 --> 00:10:11.640
It was awesome.

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:15.330
In 2006, Google was named,
for the first time, the best

00:10:15.330 --> 00:10:17.190
company to work for in America.

00:10:17.190 --> 00:10:19.440
And the year before,
Wegmans had been

00:10:19.440 --> 00:10:20.970
named best company to work for.

00:10:20.970 --> 00:10:22.740
So I was asked to be
on a panel together

00:10:22.740 --> 00:10:25.080
with this guy named
Jack DePeters, who's

00:10:25.080 --> 00:10:26.580
the COO of Wegmans.

00:10:26.580 --> 00:10:28.140
And the person
organizing the panel

00:10:28.140 --> 00:10:30.510
thought we would,
like, go at it,

00:10:30.510 --> 00:10:32.340
because Google, 30% margins.

00:10:32.340 --> 00:10:34.170
Everyone's got a
master's degree or PhD.

00:10:34.170 --> 00:10:36.450
People at the time
went to fancy schools.

00:10:36.450 --> 00:10:37.800
That's changed a little bit.

00:10:37.800 --> 00:10:41.360
The company recruits more
broadly now, thank god.

00:10:41.360 --> 00:10:44.500
And Wegmans-- it's a high
school-educated workforce,

00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:45.000
largely.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:46.090
They promote from within.

00:10:46.090 --> 00:10:46.890
It's family-owned.

00:10:46.890 --> 00:10:49.960
It's a grocer, so they have
1% or 2% profit margins.

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:52.647
And they put us on stage,
and every question-- how

00:10:52.647 --> 00:10:53.730
do you think about hiring?

00:10:53.730 --> 00:10:55.110
Well, these are the
things we look at.

00:10:55.110 --> 00:10:56.850
We look for people who are
conscientious and thoughtful

00:10:56.850 --> 00:10:57.766
and go the extra mile.

00:10:57.766 --> 00:10:59.186
Yeah, we do, too.

00:10:59.186 --> 00:11:00.560
How do you think
about promotion?

00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:03.150
We want people who really
care about their customer.

00:11:03.150 --> 00:11:04.526
We really care about the user.

00:11:04.526 --> 00:11:06.150
Everything we went
through, we do, too.

00:11:06.150 --> 00:11:06.650
We do, too.

00:11:06.650 --> 00:11:08.570
And Jack and I have
since become friends.

00:11:08.570 --> 00:11:11.070
Completely different company,
completely different industry,

00:11:11.070 --> 00:11:13.236
completely different
economics, completely different

00:11:13.236 --> 00:11:15.860
workforce--

00:11:15.860 --> 00:11:17.420
exactly the same
in terms of how we

00:11:17.420 --> 00:11:20.540
treat our people and the
experience people have.

00:11:20.540 --> 00:11:23.250
And they do it without
a ton of money.

00:11:23.250 --> 00:11:26.540
So I want to share three
examples, three kind of rules,

00:11:26.540 --> 00:11:30.500
things to take away that
I hope will be helpful.

00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:35.007
The starting point is finding
meaning in people's work.

00:11:35.007 --> 00:11:36.840
You know, I had talked
about Amy's research.

00:11:36.840 --> 00:11:40.090
This is the most
important thing.

00:11:40.090 --> 00:11:42.119
And yeah, everyone
says, OK, check.

00:11:42.119 --> 00:11:43.410
We should have meaning in work.

00:11:43.410 --> 00:11:44.534
You know, that's important.

00:11:44.534 --> 00:11:47.630
I want to give you a
sentence of two pieces.

00:11:47.630 --> 00:11:50.410
One is, what's important
in setting up a mission?

00:11:50.410 --> 00:11:52.707
And the second is the
impact this can have.

00:11:52.707 --> 00:11:55.040
So Google's mission is organize
the world's information.

00:11:55.040 --> 00:11:57.560
Make it universally
accessible and useful.

00:11:57.560 --> 00:11:59.630
What's amazing
about that is you're

00:11:59.630 --> 00:12:02.360
never going to achieve that
goal, because there's always

00:12:02.360 --> 00:12:03.230
more out there.

00:12:03.230 --> 00:12:05.069
So mission needs
to be unattainable.

00:12:05.069 --> 00:12:07.610
It needs to be something you
can always kind of move towards,

00:12:07.610 --> 00:12:08.959
but you never quite get there.

00:12:08.959 --> 00:12:11.000
If your goal is to be the
number-one rated school

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.760
in the town or the district
or the state or the nation,

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:17.600
once you get there, where
do you go from there?

00:12:17.600 --> 00:12:21.344
The second thing is having
a strong profound mission

00:12:21.344 --> 00:12:23.510
that is different from the
other institutions around

00:12:23.510 --> 00:12:27.086
you is a filter for
people who are applying.

00:12:27.086 --> 00:12:28.460
It makes people
want to be there,

00:12:28.460 --> 00:12:29.510
because there's
something different

00:12:29.510 --> 00:12:30.720
about your institution.

00:12:30.720 --> 00:12:33.965
So even in education,
every school is different.

00:12:33.965 --> 00:12:35.090
The students are different.

00:12:35.090 --> 00:12:35.840
The parents are different.

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:36.740
The community's different.

00:12:36.740 --> 00:12:37.910
The level of support
is different.

00:12:37.910 --> 00:12:38.951
The faculty is different.

00:12:38.951 --> 00:12:40.450
The administration is different.

00:12:40.450 --> 00:12:43.832
Find what is different
and special and unique.

00:12:43.832 --> 00:12:45.290
And it doesn't
matter if the school

00:12:45.290 --> 00:12:47.210
is high performing or low
performing or struggling

00:12:47.210 --> 00:12:47.710
or not.

00:12:47.710 --> 00:12:51.470
There is some magic
there, some spark there.

00:12:51.470 --> 00:12:53.800
If nothing else,
other than that spark

00:12:53.800 --> 00:12:55.850
you see in those kindergartners
when they show up

00:12:55.850 --> 00:12:58.785
for that first day, they just
want to learn everything.

00:12:58.785 --> 00:13:01.160
Like those of you who work
with kindergartners know this.

00:13:01.160 --> 00:13:04.220
What is cooler than
having somebody experience

00:13:04.220 --> 00:13:07.460
something for the first
time in their lives?

00:13:07.460 --> 00:13:11.355
Somebody who doesn't know what
a slope is, so all these kind

00:13:11.355 --> 00:13:12.980
of trivial things we
take for granted--

00:13:12.980 --> 00:13:14.563
that's an amazing
thing to connect to.

00:13:14.563 --> 00:13:16.910
So find that mission, and
then be vocal about it,

00:13:16.910 --> 00:13:18.740
and make it different
and special.

00:13:18.740 --> 00:13:22.330
The other thing, though, is
that if people are connected

00:13:22.330 --> 00:13:27.080
to that mission, they work way
harder than they will if they

00:13:27.080 --> 00:13:29.360
don't feel that connection.

00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:32.450
So Adam Grant is a
professor at Wharton,

00:13:32.450 --> 00:13:33.890
the business school, Wharton.

00:13:33.890 --> 00:13:35.280
And he's a great guy.

00:13:35.280 --> 00:13:36.890
He's a good friend,
and he's like one

00:13:36.890 --> 00:13:39.306
of these like crazy accomplished
people who you would hate

00:13:39.306 --> 00:13:41.100
if he wasn't such
a nice human being,

00:13:41.100 --> 00:13:43.070
because he was an
Olympic-caliber diver

00:13:43.070 --> 00:13:47.100
and a magician and youngest
tenure ever faculty

00:13:47.100 --> 00:13:49.375
at the university.

00:13:49.375 --> 00:13:51.750
But his original research was
around mission and meaning,

00:13:51.750 --> 00:13:53.780
and this is what got him tenure.

00:13:53.780 --> 00:13:56.905
He wanted to quantify, does
this stuff really matter?

00:13:56.905 --> 00:13:59.030
There's all these books,
"The Purpose-Driven Life,"

00:13:59.030 --> 00:14:00.830
and you go to church, and
they tell you about meaning,

00:14:00.830 --> 00:14:01.830
and everyone's like, OK.

00:14:01.830 --> 00:14:03.704
Everyone kind of performs
the same afterward,

00:14:03.704 --> 00:14:06.110
so it's not like everybody
who does one of these things

00:14:06.110 --> 00:14:08.400
or reads this book
suddenly performs better.

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:10.430
So he went to a call center.

00:14:10.430 --> 00:14:14.744
And this call center was doing
fundraising for universities,

00:14:14.744 --> 00:14:16.160
so he basically
hired these folks.

00:14:16.160 --> 00:14:18.530
You give them your alumni
list, and they call everyone

00:14:18.530 --> 00:14:19.946
on the alumni list
saying, can you

00:14:19.946 --> 00:14:23.210
please donate college to Laszlo
University or whatever it is?

00:14:23.210 --> 00:14:27.680
And these fundraisers were
raising $1,300 per week

00:14:27.680 --> 00:14:29.420
on average for the universities.

00:14:29.420 --> 00:14:31.987
And Adam thought, if I
connect them to meaning--

00:14:31.987 --> 00:14:33.570
because his research
says that works--

00:14:33.570 --> 00:14:35.370
they will get more productive.

00:14:35.370 --> 00:14:37.799
So he went out, and he
found a bunch of students

00:14:37.799 --> 00:14:39.340
who had gotten
scholarships and said,

00:14:39.340 --> 00:14:41.490
do a one-page essay
that we're going

00:14:41.490 --> 00:14:43.306
to give to these
people about the impact

00:14:43.306 --> 00:14:44.430
the scholarship had on you.

00:14:44.430 --> 00:14:47.351
And he got these
beautiful essays back.

00:14:47.351 --> 00:14:48.100
I went to college.

00:14:48.100 --> 00:14:49.000
I learned all this stuff.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:50.300
I was able to get
this great job.

00:14:50.300 --> 00:14:51.490
I've lived happily ever after.

00:14:51.490 --> 00:14:52.240
I've got a family.

00:14:52.240 --> 00:14:53.730
Like life is good.

00:14:53.730 --> 00:14:57.130
Anyone want to guess what
happened to productivity, where

00:14:57.130 --> 00:14:59.530
it went from $1,300
after these people read

00:14:59.530 --> 00:15:01.990
these one-page essays?

00:15:01.990 --> 00:15:03.430
Went down?

00:15:03.430 --> 00:15:05.470
Pessimist.

00:15:05.470 --> 00:15:08.710
Anyone else want to guess.

00:15:08.710 --> 00:15:10.580
Doubled.

00:15:10.580 --> 00:15:12.000
It's a trick question.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.420
It didn't change at all.

00:15:14.420 --> 00:15:17.617
Our pessimist was close.

00:15:17.617 --> 00:15:19.200
And they wrote about
what they learned

00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:21.699
and how much money they made--
didn't have an impact at all.

00:15:21.699 --> 00:15:23.970
And Adam, then,
completely freaked out,

00:15:23.970 --> 00:15:26.511
because he was like, oh, my god,
I'm not going to get tenure.

00:15:28.224 --> 00:15:30.140
So he went back to the
scholarship recipients,

00:15:30.140 --> 00:15:31.681
and he said, write
a different essay.

00:15:31.681 --> 00:15:35.040
Write to me about what it meant.

00:15:35.040 --> 00:15:36.980
And he got an essay
back, instead, that said,

00:15:36.980 --> 00:15:39.350
instead of like, oh, I took
this Shakespeare class.

00:15:39.350 --> 00:15:42.290
It was awesome-- that
said, I read Shakespeare

00:15:42.290 --> 00:15:45.650
for the first
time, and I learned

00:15:45.650 --> 00:15:48.350
about the English language and
where all these phrases we use

00:15:48.350 --> 00:15:49.400
come from.

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:51.830
And I learned something
about the human condition

00:15:51.830 --> 00:15:54.410
and that it's universal and
that people hundreds of years

00:15:54.410 --> 00:15:56.450
ago were going through the same
thing I'm going through today.

00:15:56.450 --> 00:15:57.080
It changed me.

00:15:57.080 --> 00:15:58.490
It affected me.

00:15:58.490 --> 00:16:00.870
And now, everybody, except
our pessimist friend,

00:16:00.870 --> 00:16:03.870
what do you think happened?

00:16:03.870 --> 00:16:05.930
No change?

00:16:05.930 --> 00:16:07.480
It went up.

00:16:07.480 --> 00:16:12.230
It went up to $3,100 a week,
more than doubling just

00:16:12.230 --> 00:16:16.810
by reading a one-page essay
talking about what this meant.

00:16:16.810 --> 00:16:19.090
And then he said, oh, I
can do better than this.

00:16:19.090 --> 00:16:21.214
So we had these students
come in, these scholarship

00:16:21.214 --> 00:16:25.640
recipients, once a month
to give a five-minute talk

00:16:25.640 --> 00:16:27.200
about what it meant.

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:33.150
And these fundraisers started
raising more than $5,000

00:16:33.150 --> 00:16:35.940
every single week.

00:16:35.940 --> 00:16:37.626
And so Adam's
replicated this study

00:16:37.626 --> 00:16:39.000
in a bunch of
different settings.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:41.010
He did a similar
thing with lifeguards,

00:16:41.010 --> 00:16:44.090
and he found that lifeguards
became 21% more attentive--

00:16:44.090 --> 00:16:47.670
you know, more time watching,
less time Facebook, whatever.

00:16:47.670 --> 00:16:51.180
He did it with tutors
and proofreaders,

00:16:51.180 --> 00:16:53.700
and he found that when
people felt more connected,

00:16:53.700 --> 00:16:55.860
when proofreaders,
editors read something

00:16:55.860 --> 00:16:59.190
about how meaningful this was
to the person whose paper was

00:16:59.190 --> 00:17:01.470
being graded and reviewed,
they spent 20% more

00:17:01.470 --> 00:17:04.319
time on every single
paper and gave more

00:17:04.319 --> 00:17:05.849
detailed and
substantive comments,

00:17:05.849 --> 00:17:08.819
just because they could
feel that connection.

00:17:08.819 --> 00:17:11.819
So it's possible to do this in
all kinds of different fields.

00:17:11.819 --> 00:17:14.790
Meaning and finding that
meaning and refreshing it

00:17:14.790 --> 00:17:16.890
and reminding people
of it again and again

00:17:16.890 --> 00:17:20.970
is essential, particularly in
a job where most of your time

00:17:20.970 --> 00:17:24.548
is spent by yourself or maybe
with you and an assistant

00:17:24.548 --> 00:17:27.089
in one setting, where you don't
have all that interaction all

00:17:27.089 --> 00:17:27.588
the time.

00:17:27.588 --> 00:17:30.300
It's not like at Google, where
you're constantly on a team,

00:17:30.300 --> 00:17:31.740
and you may be on three
or four different teams

00:17:31.740 --> 00:17:33.690
at the same time, and
you spend all your time

00:17:33.690 --> 00:17:34.880
with other people.

00:17:34.880 --> 00:17:37.051
Rekindling that spark,
rekindling that connection,

00:17:37.051 --> 00:17:39.300
and the way you do it is
through narrative and stories

00:17:39.300 --> 00:17:42.785
and exposing people to
this underlying meaning.

00:17:42.785 --> 00:17:44.160
Second thing I
want to talk about

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:48.390
is make sure people are
learning, which kind of seems

00:17:48.390 --> 00:17:50.520
self-evident.

00:17:50.520 --> 00:17:53.350
That's kind of the
whole point of teaching.

00:17:53.350 --> 00:17:55.740
But if you think about it
in a corporate environment,

00:17:55.740 --> 00:17:59.580
and if you're an
administrator or a manager,

00:17:59.580 --> 00:18:02.940
most learning happens either
through training programs.

00:18:02.940 --> 00:18:05.940
And the research on training
programs is not good.

00:18:05.940 --> 00:18:09.180
In the US, large corporations
spend $120 billion a year

00:18:09.180 --> 00:18:11.450
on training classes.

00:18:11.450 --> 00:18:13.270
$120 billion.

00:18:13.270 --> 00:18:15.855
And there's not a whole
lot of benefit to it.

00:18:15.855 --> 00:18:17.980
There's certainly almost
no measured benefit to it.

00:18:17.980 --> 00:18:20.470
I mean, if you think back
about trainings you've gone to

00:18:20.470 --> 00:18:22.522
and programs you've gone
to, how many of those

00:18:22.522 --> 00:18:23.980
things do you use
every single day?

00:18:23.980 --> 00:18:26.070
Or if you're--
this was, I guess,

00:18:26.070 --> 00:18:27.820
a four-week session
or a four-day session?

00:18:27.820 --> 00:18:28.319
Sorry.

00:18:28.319 --> 00:18:30.290
Four-day session, not four-week.

00:18:30.290 --> 00:18:30.790
If only.

00:18:30.790 --> 00:18:32.497
Four-day session.

00:18:32.497 --> 00:18:33.830
Like, play forward in your mind.

00:18:33.830 --> 00:18:35.663
I'm sure this is well
done, and the pedagogy

00:18:35.663 --> 00:18:39.100
was fantastic, but even
including this talk,

00:18:39.100 --> 00:18:41.640
you have four days of content.

00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:43.140
It's not like every
single moment,

00:18:43.140 --> 00:18:45.810
every single second is
transforming how you do things

00:18:45.810 --> 00:18:47.740
completely from here on in.

00:18:47.740 --> 00:18:50.127
There's a limited
amount we can absorb.

00:18:50.127 --> 00:18:51.960
And that challenge is
compounded by the fact

00:18:51.960 --> 00:18:54.510
that in professional settings,
what typically happens--

00:18:54.510 --> 00:18:56.700
and in academic
settings, a lot--

00:18:56.700 --> 00:19:00.426
is learning is married
to consequence.

00:19:00.426 --> 00:19:02.800
So in a corporate setting,
you have a performance review.

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:04.280
That's when you get
all your feedback,

00:19:04.280 --> 00:19:04.990
and the manager sits down.

00:19:04.990 --> 00:19:06.906
You get your performance
review, and then they

00:19:06.906 --> 00:19:09.070
tell you what your salary
increase is or maybe not.

00:19:09.070 --> 00:19:11.285
So the whole time
you're getting feedback,

00:19:11.285 --> 00:19:12.910
in the back of your
mind, you're going,

00:19:12.910 --> 00:19:15.160
oh, man, oh, man, oh,
man, oh, man, oh, man,

00:19:15.160 --> 00:19:16.330
I want to get a raise.

00:19:16.330 --> 00:19:17.720
I hope it works out.

00:19:17.720 --> 00:19:19.570
And what happens is
as soon as you tie

00:19:19.570 --> 00:19:21.010
learning to
consequence, learning

00:19:21.010 --> 00:19:23.810
shuts down, because
people become defensive.

00:19:23.810 --> 00:19:25.610
They care about the evaluation.

00:19:25.610 --> 00:19:28.400
They care about the score,
the grade, the doing well,

00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:34.057
and they focus on that rather
than, what can I learn here?

00:19:34.057 --> 00:19:36.390
Whereas as many of you know,
you learn more from failure

00:19:36.390 --> 00:19:37.884
than from success.

00:19:37.884 --> 00:19:40.300
Failure's where you dig down
and say, what did I do wrong?

00:19:40.300 --> 00:19:43.160
What can I correct?

00:19:43.160 --> 00:19:45.500
At Google, we did this thing
called the Upward Feedback

00:19:45.500 --> 00:19:48.080
Survey, and the idea was
we did a whole study called

00:19:48.080 --> 00:19:51.144
Project Oxygen, and it was about
what makes managers effective.

00:19:51.144 --> 00:19:53.060
And it turns out there's
eight things managers

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:54.226
do that make them effective.

00:19:54.226 --> 00:19:56.150
And it's things like
have a regular one on one

00:19:56.150 --> 00:19:59.510
with their people, act as
a good coach, and so on.

00:19:59.510 --> 00:20:01.924
So we turned that into a survey.

00:20:01.924 --> 00:20:03.646
Survey goes to everyone
in the company.

00:20:03.646 --> 00:20:04.520
I hope it still does.

00:20:04.520 --> 00:20:04.990
Google people?

00:20:04.990 --> 00:20:05.850
Yes, it still does?

00:20:05.850 --> 00:20:06.349
All right.

00:20:06.349 --> 00:20:07.080
OK.

00:20:07.080 --> 00:20:10.210
Because this is really
important for the company.

00:20:10.210 --> 00:20:11.820
And it's 10 or 12 questions.

00:20:11.820 --> 00:20:13.950
Does my manager act as a coach?

00:20:13.950 --> 00:20:15.840
Do we have regular one on ones?

00:20:15.840 --> 00:20:17.299
And every employee takes--

00:20:17.299 --> 00:20:19.590
I mean it's an optional
survey, but just about everyone

00:20:19.590 --> 00:20:20.465
fills out the survey.

00:20:20.465 --> 00:20:22.650
The manager gets a score.

00:20:22.650 --> 00:20:24.780
And the score is how
they did on each question

00:20:24.780 --> 00:20:27.840
from a strongly agree
to strongly disagree,

00:20:27.840 --> 00:20:29.680
and then there's
an aggregate score,

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:31.350
which is the average of those.

00:20:31.350 --> 00:20:33.810
And then the manager is also
told where that average falls

00:20:33.810 --> 00:20:36.030
in the distribution
of the company,

00:20:36.030 --> 00:20:39.012
because if everyone
gets a perfect score,

00:20:39.012 --> 00:20:39.720
there's still a--

00:20:39.720 --> 00:20:41.370
well, not if everyone
gets a perfect score,

00:20:41.370 --> 00:20:42.900
but there's still a
distribution, right?

00:20:42.900 --> 00:20:44.610
Even if everyone's
getting 90% favorable

00:20:44.610 --> 00:20:46.680
or 85% to 95%
favorable, there's still

00:20:46.680 --> 00:20:48.120
a distribution within that.

00:20:48.120 --> 00:20:50.340
So we tell managers,
here is where you are.

00:20:50.340 --> 00:20:53.040
When we started doing
it, their managers

00:20:53.040 --> 00:20:56.335
were rated 58% favorable.

00:20:56.335 --> 00:20:56.960
And that's all.

00:20:56.960 --> 00:20:58.200
We just told them,
here's the score.

00:20:58.200 --> 00:20:59.555
Here's where you are
in the distribution.

00:20:59.555 --> 00:21:01.020
You're in the top, middle--

00:21:01.020 --> 00:21:05.320
well, top third, second, or
bottom quartile of the company.

00:21:05.320 --> 00:21:07.260
And that's all we did.

00:21:07.260 --> 00:21:10.630
Then six months later,
we measured it again,

00:21:10.630 --> 00:21:13.290
and managers got better.

00:21:13.290 --> 00:21:15.037
And we measured it
again six months

00:21:15.037 --> 00:21:16.120
after that and six months.

00:21:16.120 --> 00:21:18.520
After five cycles, the
average favorability rating

00:21:18.520 --> 00:21:24.420
went from 58% to 78% favorable,
which was awesome, because I

00:21:24.420 --> 00:21:26.770
didn't have to spend any money.

00:21:26.770 --> 00:21:29.680
What happened was there
was no consequence.

00:21:29.680 --> 00:21:31.960
We just told people, here's
what your people think,

00:21:31.960 --> 00:21:34.390
which you can't debate,
because it's their opinion.

00:21:34.390 --> 00:21:35.806
Like, I don't care
what you think,

00:21:35.806 --> 00:21:38.750
and this is how they feel.

00:21:38.750 --> 00:21:41.980
And here's where you
fall in the distribution.

00:21:41.980 --> 00:21:44.490
We'll see you in six months.

00:21:44.490 --> 00:21:48.100
And most people are good people.

00:21:48.100 --> 00:21:49.810
Most people want to get better.

00:21:49.810 --> 00:21:51.310
And if you tell
them where they are,

00:21:51.310 --> 00:21:53.240
they'll kind of look
at it, and by the way,

00:21:53.240 --> 00:21:54.880
here's eight or 10
things to do differently.

00:21:54.880 --> 00:21:55.879
Here's where you scored.

00:21:55.879 --> 00:21:58.480
I'm going to do this
one that I was lower on.

00:21:58.480 --> 00:21:59.930
And they got better.

00:21:59.930 --> 00:22:01.690
It was amazing.

00:22:01.690 --> 00:22:04.300
There's a school nearby in
the town of Los Altos called

00:22:04.300 --> 00:22:05.740
the Bullis Charter School.

00:22:05.740 --> 00:22:07.390
And some of you
may do this, too.

00:22:07.390 --> 00:22:09.250
In the middle schools,
which, for them,

00:22:09.250 --> 00:22:11.140
is sixth through eighth
grade, any time a kid

00:22:11.140 --> 00:22:13.240
takes a math test,
they're allowed

00:22:13.240 --> 00:22:15.370
to retake any questions
they got wrong,

00:22:15.370 --> 00:22:17.750
and they get 50% credit for it.

00:22:17.750 --> 00:22:20.520
And the principal there,
Wanny Hersey, who's amazing,

00:22:20.520 --> 00:22:23.510
she says, it's important
that my students learn

00:22:23.510 --> 00:22:26.690
algebra and pre-algebra
and all these other things

00:22:26.690 --> 00:22:27.740
they're learning.

00:22:27.740 --> 00:22:30.500
But she told me, it's
equally important

00:22:30.500 --> 00:22:33.347
that they learn how
to learn from failure

00:22:33.347 --> 00:22:35.180
and that they learn
resilience and that they

00:22:35.180 --> 00:22:37.380
learn how to recover.

00:22:37.380 --> 00:22:39.030
So the big lesson
here is-- and I

00:22:39.030 --> 00:22:41.850
don't know how much this
applies in your world

00:22:41.850 --> 00:22:43.170
versus in the corporate world.

00:22:43.170 --> 00:22:44.834
In the corporate
world, development

00:22:44.834 --> 00:22:46.500
needs to be a completely
different thing

00:22:46.500 --> 00:22:47.695
from evaluation.

00:22:47.695 --> 00:22:50.070
And I know there's like state
standards and all this kind

00:22:50.070 --> 00:22:51.630
of-- and that's a big issue.

00:22:51.630 --> 00:22:54.930
That's way over my head
and area of expertise,

00:22:54.930 --> 00:22:58.080
but giving people the
opportunity to fail and simply

00:22:58.080 --> 00:23:00.464
learn from it is tremendous.

00:23:00.464 --> 00:23:02.130
It's the biggest gift
you can give them,

00:23:02.130 --> 00:23:04.920
and they will learn
faster and learn more.

00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:08.880
There's another Google
person named Astro Teller,

00:23:08.880 --> 00:23:11.795
and he runs Google
X. And there's

00:23:11.795 --> 00:23:13.920
a YouTube video of him
giving a talk about failure,

00:23:13.920 --> 00:23:15.129
and it's fantastic.

00:23:15.129 --> 00:23:16.920
And it's all about all
the different things

00:23:16.920 --> 00:23:21.060
they do at X to encourage
people to try things and fail

00:23:21.060 --> 00:23:21.914
and learn from it.

00:23:21.914 --> 00:23:23.080
And it's really instructive.

00:23:23.080 --> 00:23:24.300
It's worth checking out.

00:23:24.300 --> 00:23:26.370
But the big message
here is, give people

00:23:26.370 --> 00:23:29.060
that opportunity to develop.

00:23:29.060 --> 00:23:32.282
Keep it separate from
evaluation as much as you can.

00:23:32.282 --> 00:23:33.740
The last thing I
want to talk about

00:23:33.740 --> 00:23:37.370
is how to have a really
big impact on things

00:23:37.370 --> 00:23:41.040
without a lot of money and
without a lot of effort.

00:23:41.040 --> 00:23:43.190
There's a concept called nudges.

00:23:43.190 --> 00:23:46.180
So there were two professors,
Thaler and Sunstein--

00:23:46.180 --> 00:23:48.710
one's at University of
Chicago, one's at Harvard--

00:23:48.710 --> 00:23:51.860
who wrote a book 10 or 12
years ago called "Nudge."

00:23:51.860 --> 00:23:54.230
And their whole idea
was they observed

00:23:54.230 --> 00:23:57.230
that you can make small
changes in the environment

00:23:57.230 --> 00:23:59.300
or present decisions
in a certain way that

00:23:59.300 --> 00:24:04.670
drives people's behaviors
in really, really big ways.

00:24:04.670 --> 00:24:07.280
And the reason is it
goes back to how much you

00:24:07.280 --> 00:24:08.720
retain from learning
environments

00:24:08.720 --> 00:24:10.100
and from training programs.

00:24:10.100 --> 00:24:11.780
We only have so much
cognitive capacity.

00:24:11.780 --> 00:24:14.240
There's only so much we can
learn, so much we can remember,

00:24:14.240 --> 00:24:15.470
so much we can act on.

00:24:15.470 --> 00:24:18.810
We only have so much
willpower at a given time.

00:24:18.810 --> 00:24:20.780
So if you structure
your environment

00:24:20.780 --> 00:24:24.080
in a certain way or present
decisions in a certain way,

00:24:24.080 --> 00:24:27.590
you can make it easier to
make a better decision.

00:24:27.590 --> 00:24:34.230
So for example, it's
really hard to lose weight.

00:24:34.230 --> 00:24:35.026
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:24:35.026 --> 00:24:37.010
LASZLO BOCK: Yeah.

00:24:37.010 --> 00:24:38.760
Yeah.

00:24:38.760 --> 00:24:41.510
I can see I'm not alone
in knowing this and having

00:24:41.510 --> 00:24:42.290
lived this.

00:24:42.290 --> 00:24:43.250
It's really hard.

00:24:43.250 --> 00:24:45.020
Our biology
conspires against us.

00:24:45.020 --> 00:24:46.930
Our peer groups
conspire against us.

00:24:46.930 --> 00:24:48.230
You know, getting older--

00:24:48.230 --> 00:24:51.426
I mean, I'm now 44,
which, depending,

00:24:51.426 --> 00:24:53.300
feels a lot older than
I was a long time ago,

00:24:53.300 --> 00:24:56.540
but I know it's like I'm
not even halfway there.

00:24:56.540 --> 00:24:58.980
And it's just harder
to do anything.

00:24:58.980 --> 00:25:03.160
Like recovery time-- my
body needs fewer calories.

00:25:03.160 --> 00:25:05.144
In high school, I
was on a swim team.

00:25:05.144 --> 00:25:06.560
I remember coming
home, opening up

00:25:06.560 --> 00:25:09.830
the jar of peanut butter, the
crunchy style peanut butter,

00:25:09.830 --> 00:25:11.844
and just eating spoonfuls of it.

00:25:11.844 --> 00:25:14.010
And I literally the other
day was with some friends,

00:25:14.010 --> 00:25:16.093
and we were just sitting
around talking about what

00:25:16.093 --> 00:25:18.380
