00:26:55.200 --> 00:26:56.280
have all the other stuff.

00:26:56.280 --> 00:26:58.200
But it's just easier, because
every time you open it,

00:26:58.200 --> 00:26:59.430
it's staring you in the face.

00:26:59.430 --> 00:27:00.930
Same thing with
your pantry, right?

00:27:00.930 --> 00:27:04.320
Big shelf-- sugary cereal,
all the easy grab and gos.

00:27:04.320 --> 00:27:05.860
That's a nudge.

00:27:05.860 --> 00:27:08.010
And there's lots of
applications and businesses

00:27:08.010 --> 00:27:10.180
and a tremendous, tremendous
amount you can do,

00:27:10.180 --> 00:27:12.013
and it's one of the
things that over at Humu

00:27:12.013 --> 00:27:15.660
we're super, super excited
about and doing some cool stuff.

00:27:15.660 --> 00:27:17.820
I'll give you a
Google example just

00:27:17.820 --> 00:27:21.540
to prove I'm not all
about weight loss.

00:27:21.540 --> 00:27:24.420
So one of the
problems we had was

00:27:24.420 --> 00:27:27.850
we're hiring all these people,
and like in your organizations,

00:27:27.850 --> 00:27:31.380
you want people to get
productive as fast as possible.

00:27:31.380 --> 00:27:35.257
There's a difference in the
quality of and the impact

00:27:35.257 --> 00:27:36.840
of a brand-new teacher
versus somebody

00:27:36.840 --> 00:27:38.700
who's been doing it
for two or three years.

00:27:38.700 --> 00:27:40.710
And you want them to get off
that curve as fast as possible.

00:27:40.710 --> 00:27:42.090
We wanted the same thing.

00:27:42.090 --> 00:27:44.880
What we found was
the average time

00:27:44.880 --> 00:27:47.280
from when somebody joined
Google to when they were fully

00:27:47.280 --> 00:27:50.440
productive was nine months.

00:27:50.440 --> 00:27:52.440
So we're like, well, what
can we do differently?

00:27:52.440 --> 00:27:53.840
How can we accelerate that?

00:27:53.840 --> 00:27:56.026
And because we love
our science, we

00:27:56.026 --> 00:27:58.400
did a bunch of analyses about
what are these people doing

00:27:58.400 --> 00:28:00.710
differently, and what are their
managers doing differently,

00:28:00.710 --> 00:28:02.251
what are the teams
doing differently.

00:28:02.251 --> 00:28:05.030
And there's five things
that they do differently.

00:28:05.030 --> 00:28:09.590
One thing is they meet
at least two people

00:28:09.590 --> 00:28:11.780
in the first couple of
days, because it turns out

00:28:11.780 --> 00:28:14.480
building a social network
makes a huge difference.

00:28:14.480 --> 00:28:18.260
And again, I don't know
how it works in teaching,

00:28:18.260 --> 00:28:21.230
but at Google, you can actually
just show up and for two days,

00:28:21.230 --> 00:28:22.520
just kind of sit at
your desk and hang out.

00:28:22.520 --> 00:28:23.894
And there's cafes
and everything,

00:28:23.894 --> 00:28:25.370
but if you're an
introvert, you're

00:28:25.370 --> 00:28:27.920
not going to go meet
people, so meet two people.

00:28:27.920 --> 00:28:30.650
If you're an engineer, the
ones who got productive faster,

00:28:30.650 --> 00:28:32.570
they checked in code
in the first week,

00:28:32.570 --> 00:28:34.861
meaning they wrote something,
checked it in the system,

00:28:34.861 --> 00:28:36.620
got accepted within
the first week--

00:28:36.620 --> 00:28:38.460
made them more productive.

00:28:38.460 --> 00:28:44.440
Having a computer that works
and a desk, because it turns out

00:28:44.440 --> 00:28:46.990
part of what happens is when
you're new at an organization,

00:28:46.990 --> 00:28:50.302
you're particularly
open to learning.

00:28:50.302 --> 00:28:52.510
Think about the kids in the
first two weeks of school

00:28:52.510 --> 00:28:53.935
versus like 3/4 of the way.

00:28:53.935 --> 00:28:55.060
I mean they're still there.

00:28:55.060 --> 00:28:56.101
They're still interested.

00:28:56.101 --> 00:28:59.710
First two weeks, though,
you can teach them anything.

00:28:59.710 --> 00:29:00.430
I had a--

00:29:04.039 --> 00:29:05.080
I don't know what he was.

00:29:05.080 --> 00:29:06.320
He was the principal's
son, and he

00:29:06.320 --> 00:29:07.880
was in the classroom
for some reason.

00:29:07.880 --> 00:29:10.400
And I remember this is in
like second or third grade,

00:29:10.400 --> 00:29:13.230
and he was, like,
in the future, we're

00:29:13.230 --> 00:29:15.450
going to be able to--
doctors will cut slits

00:29:15.450 --> 00:29:17.075
in the side of your
neck, and we'll all

00:29:17.075 --> 00:29:19.260
breathe water like Aquaman.

00:29:19.260 --> 00:29:22.130
And for like two
years, I believed that,

00:29:22.130 --> 00:29:23.880
because it was early,
and I liked Aquaman.

00:29:23.880 --> 00:29:25.570
And I was like,
that'd be really cool.

00:29:25.570 --> 00:29:27.445
So people are more open
to learning early on.

00:29:27.445 --> 00:29:29.830
They do a whole bunch
of other things.

00:29:29.830 --> 00:29:32.649
So one option was build
all this special training.

00:29:32.649 --> 00:29:34.440
Well, we already had
an onboarding process,

00:29:34.440 --> 00:29:37.147
and it was giving us nine
months to full productivity.

00:29:37.147 --> 00:29:38.730
So instead, we said,
what's the nudge?

00:29:38.730 --> 00:29:41.500
What's a smaller invention we
can have to change behavior?

00:29:41.500 --> 00:29:44.820
So we sent a couple of emails.

00:29:44.820 --> 00:29:47.830
So anytime-- and I don't
know if this is still true,

00:29:47.830 --> 00:29:49.630
so Google people
can keep me honest--

00:29:49.630 --> 00:29:52.952
when a new employee gets hired,
the day before the first day,

00:29:52.952 --> 00:29:54.910
they get an email that
says, here's five things

00:29:54.910 --> 00:29:56.710
to do that we've shown--

00:29:56.710 --> 00:29:59.050
I see head nodding,
awesome-- that we know make

00:29:59.050 --> 00:30:01.450
people more productive sooner.

00:30:01.450 --> 00:30:04.000
The manager gets an
email two or three days

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.560
before, so that they're
ready, that says,

00:30:06.560 --> 00:30:09.670
here are five things that
you should help them with,

00:30:09.670 --> 00:30:12.646
because you can't rely on the
employee, the new hire paying

00:30:12.646 --> 00:30:14.020
attention, because
often they do.

00:30:14.020 --> 00:30:15.505
Sometimes they don't.

00:30:15.505 --> 00:30:17.380
But if you get to both
sides of the equation,

00:30:17.380 --> 00:30:19.424
you're much more likely
to have an effect.

00:30:19.424 --> 00:30:21.340
And what happened was
the time to productivity

00:30:21.340 --> 00:30:25.100
shrank from nine months
down to six months,

00:30:25.100 --> 00:30:27.039
which on the one hand,
percentage terms,

00:30:27.039 --> 00:30:28.080
that's a big improvement.

00:30:28.080 --> 00:30:29.663
On the other hand,
yeah, three months.

00:30:29.663 --> 00:30:30.320
Who cares?

00:30:30.320 --> 00:30:32.060
At the rate at
which Google hires,

00:30:32.060 --> 00:30:34.190
and if you look at
average employee lifespan,

00:30:34.190 --> 00:30:39.060
it's a 2% productivity boost
across the entire company.

00:30:39.060 --> 00:30:41.190
2% is like for every
50 employees you have,

00:30:41.190 --> 00:30:43.980
you get a free person.

00:30:43.980 --> 00:30:46.020
So think about what that
means for your schools.

00:30:46.020 --> 00:30:50.160
That's actually-- that's
a lot of free bodies.

00:30:50.160 --> 00:30:52.630
So that's another example
of a small intervention.

00:30:52.630 --> 00:30:56.362
So what does that look
like in education?

