I mean, I joke.

00:31:43.560 --> 00:31:45.601
I make light of it, but
that's like a real issue.

00:31:45.601 --> 00:31:47.554
So in East Palo
Alto, so you've got

00:31:47.554 --> 00:31:48.720
Palo Alto where Stanford is.

00:31:48.720 --> 00:31:49.960
You cross the 101 freeway.

00:31:49.960 --> 00:31:52.410
You have East Palo Alto.

00:31:52.410 --> 00:31:54.510
My wife and my daughter,
one of my girls,

00:31:54.510 --> 00:31:56.730
does volunteer work over there.

00:31:56.730 --> 00:31:58.920
More than 30% of the kids
in that school district

00:31:58.920 --> 00:32:00.866
are homeless.

00:32:00.866 --> 00:32:02.740
And I mean they live on
the street every day.

00:32:02.740 --> 00:32:03.870
I mean they don't
know where they're

00:32:03.870 --> 00:32:04.967
going to sleep that night.

00:32:04.967 --> 00:32:05.800
Could be in the car.

00:32:05.800 --> 00:32:07.150
Could be in a friend's house.

00:32:07.150 --> 00:32:08.650
That's five miles from here.

00:32:11.240 --> 00:32:12.280
So I don't know.

00:32:12.280 --> 00:32:13.580
How much is Google worth?

00:32:13.580 --> 00:32:15.047
$600 billion, $800
billion, right?

00:32:15.047 --> 00:32:17.380
You've got Apple down the
street worth almost a trillion

00:32:17.380 --> 00:32:18.010
dollars.

00:32:18.010 --> 00:32:21.020
Five miles from here,
more than 30% of the kids.

00:32:21.020 --> 00:32:23.230
So I'm joking a little,
but you all live this.

00:32:23.230 --> 00:32:29.730
Like this is-- and who's raising
their hands in this picture?

00:32:29.730 --> 00:32:30.766
Right?

00:32:30.766 --> 00:32:32.640
You've got the two girls
raising their hands.

00:32:32.640 --> 00:32:34.050
Who really raises
their hands first?

00:32:34.050 --> 00:32:36.175
First time you ask a question
in a classroom, whose

00:32:36.175 --> 00:32:38.100
hands are like, me, me, me.

00:32:38.100 --> 00:32:39.555
Is it the girls or the boys?

00:32:39.555 --> 00:32:40.470
It's the boys.

00:32:40.470 --> 00:32:42.410
I see the men raising
their hands in the room.

00:32:45.890 --> 00:32:50.000
This is what it's more like, I
think, in an actual classroom.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.270
I'm trying to find a
more realistic depiction

00:32:52.270 --> 00:32:55.218
of a California classroom.

00:32:57.970 --> 00:32:59.740
There's a couple
of problems, where

00:32:59.740 --> 00:33:03.849
I think nudging and
things like checklists,

00:33:03.849 --> 00:33:05.890
like that manager feedback
survey I talked about,

00:33:05.890 --> 00:33:09.280
might actually help a lot with,
which I kind of alluded to.

00:33:12.605 --> 00:33:14.230
Who gets called on
first in classrooms?

00:33:14.230 --> 00:33:15.490
Whose hands are up the most?

00:33:15.490 --> 00:33:16.390
Boys, right?

00:33:16.390 --> 00:33:18.240
Boys' hands go up.

00:33:18.240 --> 00:33:21.870
And it's because on average--
this is based on the science.

00:33:21.870 --> 00:33:23.440
This isn't me just
making stuff up.

00:33:23.440 --> 00:33:26.690
We had an incredible
people analytics team.

00:33:26.690 --> 00:33:28.720
So anytime before I would
talk about this stuff,

00:33:28.720 --> 00:33:31.220
while I was still here, I would
go back to the team and say,

00:33:31.220 --> 00:33:33.380
can you just make
sure this is true?

00:33:33.380 --> 00:33:35.560
And like scientifically
validated and correct

00:33:35.560 --> 00:33:38.110
and not based on what I
happened to see down the street,

00:33:38.110 --> 00:33:41.320
but, in fact, true
across humanity.

00:33:41.320 --> 00:33:44.020
Boys raise their hands
earlier, and so do men,

00:33:44.020 --> 00:33:48.550
because boys and men aren't
as hindered by certainty

00:33:48.550 --> 00:33:50.705
or knowledge as women.

00:33:50.705 --> 00:33:53.080
Men are more likely to go,
oh, I think I know the answer,

00:33:53.080 --> 00:33:56.260
whereas girls in classrooms
wait longer until they're

00:33:56.260 --> 00:33:58.480
sure of the answer.

00:33:58.480 --> 00:34:03.130
And what happens is it
creates this vicious cycle,

00:34:03.130 --> 00:34:06.220
because if I'm the teacher,
and I ask a question--

00:34:06.220 --> 00:34:09.340
2 plus 2, why is an
apple red, whatever--

00:34:09.340 --> 00:34:11.860
and the hands that
come up are boys,

00:34:11.860 --> 00:34:13.934
I want to call on somebody.

00:34:13.934 --> 00:34:15.350
And it's kind of
weird and awkward

00:34:15.350 --> 00:34:18.252
to go, like, OK, boys, I want
to hear from one of the girls,

00:34:18.252 --> 00:34:20.460
because that also is a weird
way of isolating people.

00:34:20.460 --> 00:34:21.350
So I'll call on a boy.

00:34:21.350 --> 00:34:23.141
And the boy will go,
oh, you have 2 plus 2.

00:34:23.141 --> 00:34:23.660
That's 8.

00:34:23.660 --> 00:34:25.280
I go, no, that's wrong.

00:34:25.280 --> 00:34:27.370
And I mean all the
girls know the answer,

00:34:27.370 --> 00:34:31.600
and I keep calling on boys, but
what's happened is two things.

00:34:31.600 --> 00:34:34.340
The boy has gone gotten
re-encouragement, positive

00:34:34.340 --> 00:34:36.139
encouragement,
positive reinforcement.

00:34:36.139 --> 00:34:37.130
He raised his hand.

00:34:37.130 --> 00:34:38.150
Stimulus response.

00:34:38.150 --> 00:34:39.260
Teacher called on him.

00:34:39.260 --> 00:34:40.219
Positive.

00:34:40.219 --> 00:34:43.159
The teacher's also gotten
positive reinforcement.

00:34:43.159 --> 00:34:44.300
I asked a question.

00:34:44.300 --> 00:34:46.790
This person raised their
hand, and you know what?

00:34:46.790 --> 00:34:49.370
It wasn't the right answer,
but look, they're trying.

00:34:49.370 --> 00:34:50.900
They're engaged.

00:34:50.900 --> 00:34:52.929
They're connected.

00:34:52.929 --> 00:34:57.472
And over time, we call more
on the boys than the girls.

00:34:57.472 --> 00:34:58.430
And it makes it harder.

00:34:58.430 --> 00:34:59.590
And the girls also
get a message,

00:34:59.590 --> 00:35:00.631
which is like, I'm just--

00:35:00.631 --> 00:35:03.720
I'm not going to bother.

00:35:03.720 --> 00:35:08.280
And what's crazy is I was
at an event at a girls'

00:35:08.280 --> 00:35:11.417
school, a girls' high school.

00:35:11.417 --> 00:35:13.500
And the science teacher
was doing a demonstration.

00:35:13.500 --> 00:35:16.124
It was for a bunch of adults, so
a mixed group of men and women

00:35:16.124 --> 00:35:19.090
in the classroom,
female science teacher.

00:35:19.090 --> 00:35:22.329
And the demonstration was she
had an aquarium, fish tank,

00:35:22.329 --> 00:35:22.870
and she had--

00:35:22.870 --> 00:35:24.850
I think it was a
lemon and a lime.

00:35:24.850 --> 00:35:27.672
And the question is, when
I put this in the water,

00:35:27.672 --> 00:35:28.880
is it going to float or sink?

00:35:28.880 --> 00:35:30.580
It might have been a
lime and an orange.

00:35:30.580 --> 00:35:31.621
It was two citrus fruits.

00:35:31.621 --> 00:35:33.659
I remember that for sure.

00:35:33.659 --> 00:35:35.200
And she said, what's
going to happen,

00:35:35.200 --> 00:35:36.217
and one's going to sink.

00:35:36.217 --> 00:35:36.800
One can float.

00:35:36.800 --> 00:35:38.140
What do you all think?

00:35:38.140 --> 00:35:41.540
And in the audience,
whose hands went up?

00:35:41.540 --> 00:35:43.610
All the dudes.

00:35:43.610 --> 00:35:44.960
Not me, because I knew this.

00:35:44.960 --> 00:35:46.460
I was like, I'm not
raising my hand.

00:35:46.460 --> 00:35:51.451
I know they went up, and even
though it was a girls' school,

00:35:51.451 --> 00:35:53.992
and all she does is teach girls,
she called on the men first.

00:35:56.710 --> 00:36:00.820
And it speaks to the fact that
this is just how we're wired.

00:36:00.820 --> 00:36:02.350
This is just society.

00:36:02.350 --> 00:36:05.830
This is, on average, boys
are more risk-taking.

00:36:05.830 --> 00:36:08.500
This is part of why, if
you look at birth rates,

00:36:08.500 --> 00:36:11.230
there's more boys born
than girls for every 100

00:36:11.230 --> 00:36:12.640
childbirths.

00:36:12.640 --> 00:36:14.140
We have a slightly
higher birth rate

00:36:14.140 --> 00:36:16.690
of boys than girls as
a species, and it's

00:36:16.690 --> 00:36:20.300
because roll the clock
back 10,000 years--

00:36:20.300 --> 00:36:22.810
who's more likely to die?

00:36:22.810 --> 00:36:24.829
Boys are more likely
to die, because we're

00:36:24.829 --> 00:36:26.620
more risk-seeking, and
we do stupid things,

00:36:26.620 --> 00:36:28.270
and then once you have
hunter-gatherer societies,

00:36:28.270 --> 00:36:29.950
there's a division
of labor and so on.

00:36:29.950 --> 00:36:32.540
So the reward, we are wired.

00:36:32.540 --> 00:36:35.860
We boys and men are wired to I'm
going to just put it out there,

00:36:35.860 --> 00:36:39.321
just a little bit more
on average than women.

00:36:39.321 --> 00:36:41.320
And if you look at the
population distributions,

00:36:41.320 --> 00:36:42.460
there's a lot of overlap.

00:36:42.460 --> 00:36:45.043
So it's not true that every boy
is more wired than every girl.

00:36:45.043 --> 00:36:46.720
There's a lot of overlap.

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:49.300
But we create these
vicious cycles where

00:36:49.300 --> 00:36:50.827
this happens in the classroom.

00:36:53.690 --> 00:36:56.950
There's roots of this, too,
not just in the classroom.

00:36:56.950 --> 00:36:59.470
And so part of the answer to
addressing this kind of issue

00:36:59.470 --> 00:37:01.620
and the application
of nudges isn't just--

00:37:01.620 --> 00:37:03.430
it's not your responsibility.

00:37:03.430 --> 00:37:05.930
There's a book that just came
out recently called "Everybody

00:37:05.930 --> 00:37:10.480
Lies," and it was written
by somebody who, basically,

00:37:10.480 --> 00:37:12.720
his whole trick--

00:37:12.720 --> 00:37:13.990
and it's a good trick--

00:37:13.990 --> 00:37:15.616
is he looks at--

00:37:15.616 --> 00:37:16.990
there's a product
that Google has

00:37:16.990 --> 00:37:19.750
called-- it used to be
called Google Trends.

00:37:19.750 --> 00:37:22.254
And it's also called
Ngram, N-G-R-A-M,

00:37:22.254 --> 00:37:23.920
which lets you look
at search frequency,

00:37:23.920 --> 00:37:25.810
so what are people
searching for?

00:37:25.810 --> 00:37:28.810
And the underlying data
from that is what informs--

00:37:28.810 --> 00:37:30.520
when you start typing
in Google, and it

00:37:30.520 --> 00:37:32.590
starts auto-filling in
everything you're doing,

00:37:32.590 --> 00:37:33.490
same data.

00:37:33.490 --> 00:37:36.520
So his old trick is he
thinks that better reveals

00:37:36.520 --> 00:37:39.170
who we are than what
we say on Facebook,

00:37:39.170 --> 00:37:41.517
for example, because Facebook
is who we want to be.

00:37:41.517 --> 00:37:43.600
It's like, oh, here's some
shots from my vacation,

00:37:43.600 --> 00:37:45.520
and look at my avocado
toast this morning,

00:37:45.520 --> 00:37:49.300
and my kid won this award.

00:37:49.300 --> 00:37:52.390
What we search for on
Google, nobody else sees.

00:37:52.390 --> 00:37:57.130
And his two big areas of
study in this book, he

00:37:57.130 --> 00:38:02.920
talks about politics
and the recent election,

00:38:02.920 --> 00:38:04.990
actually, the last
three elections.

00:38:04.990 --> 00:38:06.982
And quite frankly, he
talks a lot about sex,

00:38:06.982 --> 00:38:09.190
because apparently, people
use the internet for that.

00:38:09.190 --> 00:38:10.630
I did not know that.

00:38:10.630 --> 00:38:14.120
But apparently, people
search for that.

00:38:14.120 --> 00:38:15.940
But there's two
pages in his book

00:38:15.940 --> 00:38:18.640
where he talks about education.

00:38:18.640 --> 00:38:25.570
And he said, if you look at
parents of small children,

00:38:25.570 --> 00:38:28.080
if the search query is
my child is a genius,

00:38:28.080 --> 00:38:31.470
or is my child a genius,
or is my child gifted,

00:38:31.470 --> 00:38:34.320
parents of boys are
two and 1/2 times

00:38:34.320 --> 00:38:39.790
more likely to enter is my child
gifted than parents of girls,

00:38:39.790 --> 00:38:42.370
which is weird,
because at young ages,

00:38:42.370 --> 00:38:46.390
girls have better vocabularies,
perform better in schools,

00:38:46.390 --> 00:38:50.600
and are 9% more likely
to be in gifted programs.

00:38:50.600 --> 00:38:55.030
If you look at the search
query is my child overweight,

00:38:55.030 --> 00:38:56.950
they are much more
likely to look for that

00:38:56.950 --> 00:38:58.450
if it's a girl
than if it's a boy,

00:38:58.450 --> 00:39:03.200
even though there are more
overweight young girls

00:39:03.200 --> 00:39:05.210
than there are
overweight young boys.

00:39:05.210 --> 00:39:09.250
It's something like
39% versus 33%.

00:39:09.250 --> 00:39:10.810
And I'm a parent.

00:39:10.810 --> 00:39:11.990
I screw this stuff up, too.

00:39:11.990 --> 00:39:15.580
I've never done those two
searches, just for the record,

00:39:15.580 --> 00:39:18.430
but this is just the
society we live in.

00:39:18.430 --> 00:39:21.190
This is like the air we breathe,
and it's how we have evolved.

00:39:21.190 --> 00:39:22.010
It's who we are.

00:39:22.010 --> 00:39:27.059
It's like at the end of the day,
again, 10,000 years ago, you

00:39:27.059 --> 00:39:28.850
see somebody coming
towards you, or if it's

00:39:28.850 --> 00:39:31.887
somebody you know who looks
like you, sounds like you,

00:39:31.887 --> 00:39:34.220
the optimal decision is to
assume they're more like you.

00:39:34.220 --> 00:39:35.761
If it's somebody
who looks different,

00:39:35.761 --> 00:39:37.320
who's not from your
tribe, who has--

00:39:37.320 --> 00:39:39.260
it's a little safer to
be a little cautious,

00:39:39.260 --> 00:39:41.330
just like how we're wired.

00:39:41.330 --> 00:39:43.370
But today we got to
overcome this stuff,

00:39:43.370 --> 00:39:46.040
because it shows up at
home and in the classrooms.

00:39:46.040 --> 00:39:47.600
And what I would
posit, what I would

00:39:47.600 --> 00:39:50.690
put to you is that
one of the ways

00:39:50.690 --> 00:39:53.220
to address this stuff
in the classroom,

00:39:53.220 --> 00:39:55.280
in addition to everything
else that's being done,

00:39:55.280 --> 00:39:59.540
is smaller inventions and
small nudges and small actions.

00:39:59.540 --> 00:40:01.350
One of the ways we
tackled this at Google

00:40:01.350 --> 00:40:03.350
when it came to things
like performance ratings,

00:40:03.350 --> 00:40:07.075
so the way ratings happened at
Google, was I'm the manager.

00:40:07.075 --> 00:40:09.200
I give my employer a rating,
but before it's final,

00:40:09.200 --> 00:40:11.030
I sit down with a bunch
of other managers,

00:40:11.030 --> 00:40:12.655
and we all discuss our ratings.

00:40:12.655 --> 00:40:14.030
And there's all
these things that

00:40:14.030 --> 00:40:16.629
happen in our brain, independent
of gender or ethnicity,

00:40:16.629 --> 00:40:18.170
that causes us to
make bad decisions.

00:40:18.170 --> 00:40:20.720
There's something
called recency bias,

00:40:20.720 --> 00:40:22.850
and you have this
in education, too.

00:40:22.850 --> 00:40:26.179
If I just had a meeting with
someone, and it was awesome,

00:40:26.179 --> 00:40:28.470
and then two days later, I'm
doing performance reviews,

00:40:28.470 --> 00:40:30.830
I'm going to give them a
higher rating, because I just

00:40:30.830 --> 00:40:31.610
had this meeting with Sally.

00:40:31.610 --> 00:40:34.070
She was fantastic, and now,
of course, she's awesome.

00:40:34.070 --> 00:40:36.520
It doesn't matter what she did
the prior six or 12 months.

00:40:36.520 --> 00:40:38.369
It's recency bias.

00:40:38.369 --> 00:40:39.410
Same thing in classrooms.

00:40:39.410 --> 00:40:41.330
You have a great interaction
with the kid on the playground

00:40:41.330 --> 00:40:43.310
or something happens, you're
more likely to assess them

00:40:43.310 --> 00:40:44.768
better subconsciously,
particularly

00:40:44.768 --> 00:40:46.580
on qualitative subjects.

00:40:46.580 --> 00:40:49.110
Math is math, but
everything else, it's tough.

00:40:49.110 --> 00:40:50.300
This stuff shows up.

00:40:50.300 --> 00:40:53.390
So what we did was we had a
one-page handout with here's

00:40:53.390 --> 00:40:56.510
a bunch of biases, and you
just have this in front of you

00:40:56.510 --> 00:40:58.270
when you do ratings.

00:40:58.270 --> 00:41:01.970
And it reminds you, it's
a trigger, it's a nudge,

00:41:01.970 --> 00:41:06.170
and a checklist that says,
here's a better way to do it.

00:41:06.170 --> 00:41:07.870
And this I say,
again, like this part

00:41:07.870 --> 00:41:11.980
with humility, because in this
field, you are the experts.

00:41:11.980 --> 00:41:14.709
I just have an opinion, and
everyone's got one of those.

00:41:14.709 --> 00:41:16.750
But I would imagine there's
a lot of small things

00:41:16.750 --> 00:41:18.850
you can do in terms of--

00:41:18.850 --> 00:41:21.460
and I would do it
in terms of trying

00:41:21.460 --> 00:41:22.720
one thing for three months.

00:41:22.720 --> 00:41:23.830
It's not like here's
six things we're

00:41:23.830 --> 00:41:25.038
going to do to revamp things.

00:41:25.038 --> 00:41:28.390
But if you believe what I shared
with you about boys and girls

00:41:28.390 --> 00:41:30.820
raising their
hands, tell teachers

00:41:30.820 --> 00:41:35.160
like, hey, for the next month,
make sure that you alternate

00:41:35.160 --> 00:41:36.870
calling on a boy or girl.

00:41:36.870 --> 00:41:37.717
Just keep it 50-50.

00:41:37.717 --> 00:41:39.300
Or you can go two
to one the other way

00:41:39.300 --> 00:41:41.860
if you really want to be crazy.

00:41:41.860 --> 00:41:44.020
But just try it, and then
at the end of the month,

00:41:44.020 --> 00:41:46.790
let's all sit together and
see if that made a difference.

00:41:46.790 --> 00:41:48.498
And if you want to
get sciencey about it,

00:41:48.498 --> 00:41:51.832
say, OK, we're going to give
the kids a test on something

00:41:51.832 --> 00:41:53.290
or measurement of
their trajectory,

00:41:53.290 --> 00:41:56.697
and see if that
trajectory has changed.

00:41:56.697 --> 00:41:58.780
Or compare first and second
trimester performance,

00:41:58.780 --> 00:42:00.064
or something like that.

00:42:00.064 --> 00:42:01.480
But a small
intervention like that

00:42:01.480 --> 00:42:03.140
can have a huge, huge impact.

00:42:03.140 --> 00:42:05.120
So pick small things
people can do.

00:42:05.120 --> 00:42:07.450
And second thing is, then,
remind them about this stuff

00:42:07.450 --> 00:42:07.840
over time.

00:42:07.840 --> 00:42:10.270
Maybe there's two or three you
rotate through over a year,

00:42:10.270 --> 00:42:12.539
or maybe there's like--

00:42:12.539 --> 00:42:14.080
I mean, there's a
handout people use.

00:42:14.080 --> 00:42:15.163
Maybe there's a checklist.

00:42:15.163 --> 00:42:17.170
But keep coming back
to it periodically,

00:42:17.170 --> 00:42:18.429
and you will see changes.

00:42:18.429 --> 00:42:20.720
But it's these little tiny
things, which, it turns out,

00:42:20.720 --> 00:42:24.100
are actually easy
to do in the moment,

00:42:24.100 --> 00:42:27.250
as long you don't swamp people
with a lot of direction,

