completely public.

00:53:20.020 --> 00:53:23.030
So it was one of the
first things we shared,

00:53:23.030 --> 00:53:24.954
and the public
name was Project--

00:53:24.954 --> 00:53:26.870
well, the internal name,
which you can Google,

00:53:26.870 --> 00:53:30.260
is Project Oxygen, because
the idea is managers,

00:53:30.260 --> 00:53:32.570
good managers are as
essential as oxygen.

00:53:32.570 --> 00:53:34.380
There's resources
on the Rework site.

00:53:34.380 --> 00:53:38.260
There's also, if you just Google
Project Oxygen New York Times,

00:53:38.260 --> 00:53:40.010
there's a great "New
York Times" write-up.

00:53:40.010 --> 00:53:42.260
They actually eventually did a
Harvard Business Review case.

00:53:42.260 --> 00:53:44.180
But if you just look at the
"New York Times" write-up,

00:53:44.180 --> 00:53:46.250
it's got the eight
factors, and then there's

00:53:46.250 --> 00:53:49.500
three factors which are
really bad indicators.

00:53:49.500 --> 00:53:51.530
And it's basically, you
ask, does the manager

00:53:51.530 --> 00:53:53.780
do these things, or does the
employee do these things?

00:53:53.780 --> 00:53:55.410
And whatever your scale is--

00:53:55.410 --> 00:53:57.590
high to low, agree to disagree.

00:53:57.590 --> 00:53:58.629
That's it.

00:53:58.629 --> 00:54:00.170
And then you just
sort of-- everybody

00:54:00.170 --> 00:54:01.670
gets a report back that
says, here's your score

00:54:01.670 --> 00:54:04.071
on this question, and here's
the average of these scores.

00:54:04.071 --> 00:54:05.570
And here's how your
average compares

00:54:05.570 --> 00:54:06.694
to everyone else's average.

00:54:06.694 --> 00:54:08.527
That is-- that's
the whole thing.

00:54:08.527 --> 00:54:10.610
But if you go on the Rework
site, you can find it,

00:54:10.610 --> 00:54:12.950
or the "New York Times"
article is great for it.

00:54:12.950 --> 00:54:16.610
I actually-- I think that's one
of the more impactful things

00:54:16.610 --> 00:54:21.139
we did, because it
touched everyone.

00:54:21.139 --> 00:54:22.680
There was a clear,
measurable effect,

00:54:22.680 --> 00:54:24.650
so it was kind of
self-reinforcing.

00:54:24.650 --> 00:54:30.200
And one of the hard things about
leading large organizations

00:54:30.200 --> 00:54:34.130
is there's very rarely a
one size fits all answer.

00:54:34.130 --> 00:54:36.780
And even in small
organizations, that's tough.

00:54:36.780 --> 00:54:40.370
And what was beautiful
about this was

00:54:40.370 --> 00:54:43.437
I didn't have to know what
training to send you to

00:54:43.437 --> 00:54:45.020
or which of these
things you were weak

00:54:45.020 --> 00:54:46.772
on, or across the
5,000 managers,

00:54:46.772 --> 00:54:48.980
when we started doing this,
like who is good at what,

00:54:48.980 --> 00:54:50.060
and customize.

00:54:50.060 --> 00:54:52.160
I just told everyone,
these are the things.

00:54:52.160 --> 00:54:54.580
And then this goes back to
the freedom is free thing.

00:54:54.580 --> 00:54:55.640
You get better at it.

00:54:55.640 --> 00:54:57.399
You figure out
how to get better.

00:54:57.399 --> 00:54:59.690
The trick was-- and this is
not in the "New York Times"

00:54:59.690 --> 00:55:01.520
write-up, the last
question on the survey

00:55:01.520 --> 00:55:05.810
is always my manager shares
these results with me,

00:55:05.810 --> 00:55:09.400
because that makes the manager
accountable to the team.

00:55:09.400 --> 00:55:11.150
And the only way you
get 100% is if you're

00:55:11.150 --> 00:55:12.926
really good at sharing
the results back,

00:55:12.926 --> 00:55:15.050
and that causes the manager
to improve, work on it,

00:55:15.050 --> 00:55:16.400
get better.

00:55:16.400 --> 00:55:18.970
But yeah, it had a
really big impact.

00:55:18.970 --> 00:55:21.842
I do think the rankings
are a little goofy.

00:55:21.842 --> 00:55:24.050
I mean it's always like the
high-rated companies that

00:55:24.050 --> 00:55:25.760
are like, oh, the
rankings don't matter.

00:55:25.760 --> 00:55:28.910
But I think there's some
weirdness behind it,

00:55:28.910 --> 00:55:33.500
so yeah, take that with a
grain of salt. What else,

00:55:33.500 --> 00:55:34.000
if anything?

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:35.279
How are we on time?

00:55:35.279 --> 00:55:37.820
SPEAKER: Maybe time for one more
question, if anybody has it.

00:55:37.820 --> 00:55:39.650
Otherwise.

00:55:39.650 --> 00:55:41.190
LASZLO BOCK: Any last questions?

00:55:41.190 --> 00:55:43.040
SPEAKER: Burning questions?

00:55:43.040 --> 00:55:43.554
All right.

00:55:43.554 --> 00:55:44.720
Well, then-- oh, we got one.

00:55:44.720 --> 00:55:45.720
LASZLO BOCK: Is that OK?

00:55:45.720 --> 00:55:46.314
SPEAKER: Yep.

00:55:46.314 --> 00:55:49.618
AUDIENCE: As a principal
of low income kids,

00:55:49.618 --> 00:55:51.570
what can I do to prepare
them for a job here?

00:55:51.570 --> 00:55:53.444
LASZLO BOCK: As principal
of low income kids,

00:55:53.444 --> 00:55:56.260
what can I do to prepare
them for a job here?

00:55:56.260 --> 00:56:00.880
The research suggests
the most important thing

00:56:00.880 --> 00:56:06.040
that kids learn in sort of pre-K
through second or fourth grade

00:56:06.040 --> 00:56:09.550
is our social and
emotional skills,

00:56:09.550 --> 00:56:11.600
not the academic skills.

00:56:11.600 --> 00:56:13.930
The ability to
function in a team,

00:56:13.930 --> 00:56:16.390
the ability to
delay gratification,

00:56:16.390 --> 00:56:20.090
the ability to show resilience
in the face of failure--

00:56:20.090 --> 00:56:22.330
those are, if you
look at what incomes

00:56:22.330 --> 00:56:26.690
are 15 and 20 years out
and job level attained,

00:56:26.690 --> 00:56:30.020
those are the things that
most predict performance.

00:56:30.020 --> 00:56:30.742
Sorry?

00:56:30.742 --> 00:56:32.010
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:56:32.010 --> 00:56:35.140
LASZLO BOCK: Yeah,
they were resilience

00:56:35.140 --> 00:56:37.200
in the face of failure.

00:56:37.200 --> 00:56:39.927
What did I say?

00:56:39.927 --> 00:56:41.760
Well, social emotional
skills is a high one,

00:56:41.760 --> 00:56:43.470
but then the examples were--
there's a whole cluster

00:56:43.470 --> 00:56:44.710
of things underneath that.

00:56:44.710 --> 00:56:46.320
So team and
collaboration skills.

00:56:46.320 --> 00:56:47.940
What was the second one?

00:56:47.940 --> 00:56:50.070
Self-regulation, yeah.

00:56:50.070 --> 00:56:53.130
Yeah, there goes my credibility.

00:56:53.130 --> 00:56:54.630
But no, those are
the attributes,

00:56:54.630 --> 00:56:58.704
which would stick with
you throughout life.

00:56:58.704 --> 00:57:00.120
For Google
specifically-- and then

00:57:00.120 --> 00:57:02.495
I'll close with one other
thing, which your question just

00:57:02.495 --> 00:57:06.210
reminded me of, because it
relates to low income kids.

00:57:06.210 --> 00:57:10.950
To get into Google, it's funny.

00:57:10.950 --> 00:57:12.240
I always used to index high.

00:57:12.240 --> 00:57:14.115
Like actually at Humu,
I just hired somebody,

00:57:14.115 --> 00:57:16.530
because what I saw
on their resume

00:57:16.530 --> 00:57:18.720
was that they went to San
Jose State, so bachelor's

00:57:18.720 --> 00:57:20.310
and master's at San Jose State.

00:57:20.310 --> 00:57:22.894
And they did well and
strong academic performance

00:57:22.894 --> 00:57:24.060
for our People Science team.

00:57:24.060 --> 00:57:26.880
But the reason I zeroed in
on that for this young woman

00:57:26.880 --> 00:57:30.870
was you go to a state school
for a couple of reasons.

00:57:30.870 --> 00:57:32.600
One is you're
smart, but you don't

00:57:32.600 --> 00:57:35.210
have the role models to tell
you, here's the process,

00:57:35.210 --> 00:57:37.376
and here's how you navigate
it, which I didn't have.

00:57:37.376 --> 00:57:38.090
I lucked into it.

00:57:38.090 --> 00:57:39.860
Or you just don't
have the money.

00:57:39.860 --> 00:57:40.654
And so I meet her.

00:57:40.654 --> 00:57:41.570
We start interviewing.

00:57:41.570 --> 00:57:42.069
We hire her.

00:57:42.069 --> 00:57:42.770
She's amazing.

00:57:42.770 --> 00:57:45.830
And then eventually, I ask
her, what's your story?

00:57:45.830 --> 00:57:47.990
And she's in her late 20s.

00:57:47.990 --> 00:57:49.574
She's had 13 jobs.

00:57:49.574 --> 00:57:50.990
All the time she
was an undergrad,

00:57:50.990 --> 00:57:53.270
she was a manager at a
Claire's like in a mall, one

00:57:53.270 --> 00:57:55.800
of these earring places.

00:57:55.800 --> 00:57:59.210
She said she's pierced
over 2,000 ears.

00:57:59.210 --> 00:58:02.280
So when I was at Google, one
of the things I'd look for

00:58:02.280 --> 00:58:04.280
is if somebody went to a
community college, then

00:58:04.280 --> 00:58:06.350
transferred, that's a signal.

00:58:06.350 --> 00:58:08.684
If somebody went to a state
school and performed well,

00:58:08.684 --> 00:58:09.350
that's a signal.

00:58:09.350 --> 00:58:11.930
If somebody had a
job that was not--

00:58:11.930 --> 00:58:15.530
I went to Kenya and
helped build churches,

00:58:15.530 --> 00:58:18.410
but the job was like, you know,
I worked at a Gas and Sip.

00:58:18.410 --> 00:58:19.700
I worked at a 7-Eleven.

00:58:19.700 --> 00:58:23.330
Like I wanted to see those kids.

00:58:23.330 --> 00:58:26.600
The ideal path, of course,
is you do well academically.

00:58:26.600 --> 00:58:28.100
So the conventional
advice, and this

00:58:28.100 --> 00:58:31.790
is like for any company, the way
to stand out-- so for Google,

00:58:31.790 --> 00:58:34.190
perform well at
whatever you are.

00:58:34.190 --> 00:58:37.770
Show an increasing rate of
progression in your results,

00:58:37.770 --> 00:58:40.380
so not just I did well
here, and I did well here,

00:58:40.380 --> 00:58:43.255
but I did well here faster.

00:58:43.255 --> 00:58:45.630
Once you're in the workforce,
if you're getting promoted,

00:58:45.630 --> 00:58:47.921
if you're getting promoted
faster than every two years,

00:58:47.921 --> 00:58:50.100
that's a good signal.

00:58:50.100 --> 00:58:52.924
But for students, absolutely,
identify if you're

00:58:52.924 --> 00:58:54.090
from a low income household.

00:58:54.090 --> 00:58:56.100
Identify if you're the
first in your family.

00:58:56.100 --> 00:58:58.879
Identify-- and it's not
about writing a sob story.

00:58:58.879 --> 00:59:00.420
It's just like put
it in your resume.

00:59:00.420 --> 00:59:03.270
This is the context, right?

00:59:03.270 --> 00:59:04.860
That's really, really important.

00:59:04.860 --> 00:59:09.880
The thing-- the generic advice
is for most organizations--

00:59:09.880 --> 00:59:13.380
so Google's a bit of a
special case, and I'm biased.

00:59:13.380 --> 00:59:15.397
Most organizations
focus on brands,

00:59:15.397 --> 00:59:17.730
and they focus on academics
and all these stupid things.

00:59:17.730 --> 00:59:20.317
So the way to cheat your
way on that side is--

00:59:20.317 --> 00:59:22.650
because not everyone gets to
work for Procter and Gamble

00:59:22.650 --> 00:59:24.774
or some fancy brand everyone's
going to recognize--

00:59:24.774 --> 00:59:27.210
is wherever you work, try
to do project work that

00:59:27.210 --> 00:59:29.310
connects to a fancy brand.

00:59:29.310 --> 00:59:31.110
And mention that in
the bullet points

00:59:31.110 --> 00:59:33.049
on your resume or
your application,

00:59:33.049 --> 00:59:34.590
because people will
be scanning that.

00:59:34.590 --> 00:59:36.330
And the first people who kind
of make it through the filter--

00:59:36.330 --> 00:59:38.980
again, not at Google, but
like in the real world--

00:59:38.980 --> 00:59:40.727
the first people
are the people who

00:59:40.727 --> 00:59:42.810
went to all the right
schools and right companies.

00:59:42.810 --> 00:59:45.120
The next people are the
people whose resumes

00:59:45.120 --> 00:59:47.370
mention those words,
and they get called up.

00:59:47.370 --> 00:59:50.340
And then eventually, you
get to everybody else.

00:59:50.340 --> 00:59:52.602
So that's signaling and
branding is really important.

00:59:52.602 --> 00:59:54.060
The thing I'll
close on, if I can--

00:59:56.961 --> 00:59:59.460
actually, my wife has a friend
named Michele Colbert Krantz,

00:59:59.460 --> 01:00:02.910
who's a principal at a school
called La Mesa Junior High

01:00:02.910 --> 01:00:04.680
School in Santa
Clarita, California.

01:00:04.680 --> 01:00:06.960
So it's a few hundred
miles south of here.

01:00:06.960 --> 01:00:08.430
It's just north of Los Angeles.

01:00:08.430 --> 01:00:13.470
And largely Hispanic school,
largely low income school--

01:00:13.470 --> 01:00:16.200
she wanted to be at that
school for those reasons.

01:00:16.200 --> 01:00:19.140
And she does a couple of
things that are really amazing,

01:00:19.140 --> 01:00:21.240
and the students love
her, and the school is now

01:00:21.240 --> 01:00:22.350
a high-performing school.

01:00:25.070 --> 01:00:26.210
And it's a lot of work.

01:00:26.210 --> 01:00:29.270
She greets every kid every
morning, shakes their hand,

01:00:29.270 --> 01:00:32.190
looks them in the
eye, says their name.

01:00:32.190 --> 01:00:33.480
And the other thing she does--

01:00:33.480 --> 01:00:37.290
and I was reminded of it,
because you guys had these.

01:00:39.960 --> 01:00:42.990
And all I could see was
this kind and brave, so

01:00:42.990 --> 01:00:44.330
she does this thing, where--

01:00:44.330 --> 01:00:46.230
and you know, there's
like Kind bars.

01:00:46.230 --> 01:00:51.760
So what Michele does, and
she's done this for years,

01:00:51.760 --> 01:00:54.350
she gives out Kudos
bars, because she

01:00:54.350 --> 01:00:55.449
doesn't have a budget.

01:00:55.449 --> 01:00:56.490
It's a low income school.

01:00:56.490 --> 01:00:59.060
So she goes to Costco,
buys like 40 Kudos bars,

01:00:59.060 --> 01:01:01.550
and when she sees a kid
doing something well,

01:01:01.550 --> 01:01:04.220
or she sees a staff member
doing something well,

01:01:04.220 --> 01:01:07.220
she'll carry three or
four in her pocket.

01:01:07.220 --> 01:01:08.660
She just gifts the kid.

01:01:08.660 --> 01:01:12.930
And what's wild is they
don't always eat them,

01:01:12.930 --> 01:01:14.195
because it's a trophy.

01:01:14.195 --> 01:01:14.820
It's a memento.

01:01:14.820 --> 01:01:16.624
It means something.

01:01:16.624 --> 01:01:17.790
And it costs almost nothing.

01:01:20.310 --> 01:01:22.560
Those are the small nudges,
the small interventions.

01:01:22.560 --> 01:01:24.670
It is incredibly hard.

01:01:24.670 --> 01:01:26.670
Like, you guys don't get
the kids for that long.

01:01:26.670 --> 01:01:27.990
I mean, you're the
source of stability,

01:01:27.990 --> 01:01:29.950
but you don't actually
have them for that long.

01:01:29.950 --> 01:01:31.033
They're in your classroom.

01:01:31.033 --> 01:01:32.070
Then they move on.

01:01:32.070 --> 01:01:34.385
And teaching is a solitary
profession in a lot of ways.

01:01:34.385 --> 01:01:36.510
I mean, you're doing what
you do in your classroom.

01:01:36.510 --> 01:01:37.320
Yes, you can compare notes.

01:01:37.320 --> 01:01:38.110
Yes, you do.

01:01:38.110 --> 01:01:39.780
But it's like you
doing this thing,

01:01:39.780 --> 01:01:41.820
and let me try something
differently this year,

01:01:41.820 --> 01:01:45.030
and I'll know in 20 years
if it was a good idea.

01:01:45.030 --> 01:01:46.830
That's really hard.

01:01:46.830 --> 01:01:50.827
But there's so many small little
things that stick with people.

01:01:50.827 --> 01:01:52.660
And for those of you
who are administrators,

01:01:52.660 --> 01:01:54.265
I know you're all
going to be coaches.

01:01:54.265 --> 01:01:56.360
And I don't know what the
content is that you guys have,

01:01:56.360 --> 01:01:57.610
so I hope I don't screw it up.

01:01:57.610 --> 01:01:59.830
But really try to focus in.

01:01:59.830 --> 01:02:02.530
My advice would be, what are the
small things you can ask people

01:02:02.530 --> 01:02:05.920
to change and that they
can try again and again

01:02:05.920 --> 01:02:08.080
and run in small experiments?

01:02:08.080 --> 01:02:09.760
So they try something.

01:02:09.760 --> 01:02:10.930
Go try this for two weeks.

01:02:10.930 --> 01:02:12.610
Let's talk again and
see how it works.

01:02:12.610 --> 01:02:13.300
Now let's try.

01:02:13.300 --> 01:02:15.769
Now stop doing it for
two weeks, because you

01:02:15.769 --> 01:02:18.060
want the people on the other
end to experience not just

01:02:18.060 --> 01:02:19.602
that it worked, if
it worked, but you

01:02:19.602 --> 01:02:22.060
wanted them to experience what
happens if you take it away.

01:02:22.060 --> 01:02:23.510
So do the 50-50 calling on kids.

01:02:23.510 --> 01:02:24.990
Then stop.

01:02:24.990 --> 01:02:27.389
See what happens, because
you want people to feel this,

01:02:27.389 --> 01:02:28.680
if you want to change behavior.

01:02:28.680 --> 01:02:31.520
You want that connection.

01:02:31.520 --> 01:02:34.020
And I can't wait to
hear what you all do.

01:02:34.020 --> 01:02:34.880
It's super exciting.

01:02:34.880 --> 01:02:36.560
So thank you all
for having me here.

01:02:36.560 --> 01:02:40.510
[APPLAUSE]

